title: Getting Elected Can Turn On Plain Old Luck
meta_description:
WHEN the mayoral election that consumed this Hudson River village ended last year in a draw, there was no runoff vote to settle the race, no duel on Main Street -- nothing that inspired any real sense of closure.

Instead, the Board of Trustees collected four quarters bearing the image of the Statue of Liberty, another four with eagles, and dropped them into a little purple pouch. When Richard J. Livingston, a trustee at the time, plucked a Statue of Liberty coin from the bag, Dennis Flood, the five-term Republican incumbent, was returned to power, defeating Erin Malloy, a Democrat.

title: QUICK BITE: Fort Lee; A Chain Restaurant Unbound
meta_description:
Chain restaurants in northern New Jersey are a dime a couple of dozen and, more often than not, you can expect nothing short of absolute mediocrity in both the food and the service. Very rarely you may find individual establishments that do an exceptional job.

One such place is the recently opened Original Pancake House, in Fort Lee, where Peter Rentzis and his family have created a magnet for breakfast lovers. They use only fresh ingredients, cooked from scratch, and the only links they have to the 90-store parent chain are a book of recipes and the right to use its trademarks.

title: Paid Notice: Deaths   SACKETT, ROSS D.
meta_description: SACKETT--Ross D. age 77, of Fontana, WI died Thursday, August 16, 2007 at Walworth, WI. He was born March 26, 1930 in Chicago, IL to parents DeForest and Margaret (Ross) Sackett. He was united in marriage to Marvyda Wild in September of 1951 at Mattoon, IL. Some of Mr. Sackett's more recent accomplishments include Holt, Rinehart, & Winston, Inc., in New York: Engineering and Science Editor; Vice President, General Manager College Department, Executive Vice President Director, and President; CBS in New York: president, CBS Education and Publishing Group, Director CBS, and Director CBS Foundation. For Encyclopedia Britannica Education Corporation of Chicago, IL, he was President and CEO, Director and member of the executive committee of Encyclopedia Britannica, Inc., member of the Editorial Board, Chairman Voting Trust, Encyclopedia Britannica Educational Corporation. Mr. Sackett was also an author, owner of several businesses, restorer of Victorian homes, and was an avid historian. He is survived by his wife Skip of 56 years, sons Scott and Stuart, daughters Cynthia and Amy, as well as 12 grandchildren and numerous friends. He was preceded in death by his son Dave. He loved books, architecture, sports and hiking.

title: White Plains Report Card
meta_description:
IN the eight years that Joseph M. Delfino has been its mayor, White Plains has seen $2 billion worth of construction transform the downtown into a neighborhood of luxury apartments, shops, restaurants and movie theaters. It is a change that Mr. Delfino, a Republican, likes to crow about, and he says there's more where that come from in the next four years.

But Dennis Power, Mr. Delfino's Democratic challenger, sees a downside to the renaissance: It is speeding ahead without restraint, he says. The boom has not benefited the city's nearly 54,000 residents, he said. Instead it has left them on the outside looking in as gleaming skyscrapers rise quickly around them.

meta_description:
BY the time he had served for 31 years as district attorney of Nassau County, Denis Dillon was probably known as much for the kinds of things he did not do as for those he did.

For example, he did not seek the death penalty in any murder trial, and he refused to handle cases involving abortion-clinic protesters, farming them out to neighboring jurisdictions. Mr. Dillon, 71, attributed both of those policies to his personal convictions and to the tenets of his Roman Catholic faith.

title: Corrections
meta_description: An article on Friday about allegations of deficiencies in federally financed cancer treatment trials at the Carle Cancer Center in Urbana, Ill., misstated federal oversight of such community research sites. While federal officials have not conducted a systematic patient safety review of the community research program with the level of scrutiny they are now applying to Carle, the National Cancer Institute audits such centers at least once every 36 months and has evaluated the overall program several times, most recently in 2007. It is not true that federal officials “have never conducted a systematic review” of the program.

title: Prufrock: Conservative Magazines Today, Johnny Cash's Visit to Folsom Prison at 50, and in Praise of Pen and Paper
meta_description:
Reviews and News:
Johnny Cash’s visit to Folsom prison at 50: “When Cash sang the words, ‘I shot a man in Reno, just to watch him die,’ the inmates can be heard cheering wildly. In reality, those cheers were added post-recording by producer Bob Johnston because the inmates were too afraid to show emotion lest they suffer reprisals by the guards.
Some writing advice from Mark Bauerlein: “If you teach high school or college students, or have kids who are passing through those places, and if your duties include grading papers, or you watch your kids struggle with writing assignments, I have a piece of advice. Tell them to try composing by hand, with pen and paper, not on the keyboard.”
Andrew Cohen explains why Judge Rosemarie Aquilina’s demeanor and final words in the Larry Nassar sexual abuse case were inappropriate: “I followed the case. I followed the hearing. The impression I got was that the judge was using the forum to strive for some sort of cathartic awakening on behalf of Nassar’s victims and victims of sexual assault more broadly. There is nothing wrong with that. It’s a noble cause. But there is no place for that in an American courtroom, no matter how much we acknowledge that victims should have a significant role in sentencing. No judge in America should play the role of advocate for victims or prosecutors. No judge in America can play that role if we are to respect our rule of law.”

meta_description: SCHWARZ--Julia Bach. In memory of our dear aunt, Julia Bach Schwarz. Devoted mother of John Squire and Jill Keech, beloved sister of Margery Bach Brodsky and Emily Bach Bishop, and fast friend to all of our families' offspring. Her son and daughter reciprocated their mother's love with deep devotion. With selfless grace, Julia built community wherever she lived; in New York City where she was born on March 28, 1913, in Tucson, Arizona where she lived for many years, and in Gaithersburg, Maryland where she died on March 11, 2015. When she could no longer travel the world, it was her love of reading that sustained her. All who knew her sent her books. The last of her generation, she was our sustaining matriarch. Biondi, Senior Vice President of Development, Community Relations & Marketing. Rich was truly a giant in the business, civic, and philanthropic communities in Westchester County. He embodied leadership, touching many lives through his involvement with community organizations too numerous to mention. Throughout his illness, Rich gained strength from coming to work, remaining active in the community, and from daily interactions with colleagues and friends. His courage was an inspiration to all of us. He was a man of great compassion and generosity, an outstanding citizen and an extraordinary family man. We extend our deepest sympathies to his bride Maureen, mother Jennie, children Richard P. Biondi II (Kelley) and Jennifer O'Sullivan (Kevin), and his five grandchildren. The entire community has lost a remarkable man who leaves a lasting legacy. Paul M. Weissman Chairman, Board of Directors Jon B. Schandler President and CEO

title: Jets' Kicker Wants the Opportunity to Try to Hit the Long Ball
meta_description:
Late in the third quarter Sunday at Dolphins Stadium, the Jets drove to the Miami 30-yard line, where they faced third-and-13. According to the numbers that Mike Westhoff, the special-teams coach, had fed Coach Herman Edwards after gauging place-kicker Mike Nugent's performance during pregame warm-ups, the Jets were in Nugent's field-goal range.

Then left tackle Adrian Jones twitched at the line and was called for a false start. Just like that, Nugent's foot was taken out of play. The 5-yard penalty moved the Jets out of his range, in the estimation of Westhoff.

meta_description: Prices for business insurance are continuing to soar and American International Group chief executive Maurice R Greenberg says he expects no letup at least through next year; says premiums on commercial coverages jumped more than 34 percent and contributed significantly to 37 percent increase in net profit in second quarter; company reports net income of $1.8 billion compared with $1.3 billion year earlier (M)

title: NEWS SUMMARY
meta_description:
INTERNATIONAL A3-27

Suicide Bombers Kill 36 At Iraqi Police Academy
Powerful explosions from two suicide bombs ripped through the capital's main police academy, killing at least 36 police officers and wounding 72 others, an Interior Ministry official and the American military said. A1

Vice President Dick Cheney, appearing before more than 2,000 troops in northern New York, said the administration has ''a comprehensive strategy for victory'' in Iraq and is making progress in training Iraqi troops. A27

Rice Criticized in Europe
Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice was pelted with criticism about covert prisons and a mistaken, secret arrest, as she grappled with what has become an incendiary issue in Europe. A1

German Claims Abuse by U.S.
A German citizen who says he was abducted in 2003, beaten and taken to Afghanistan by American agents in what was apparently a case of mistaken identity, filed suit in federal court against George J. Tenet, the former C.I.A. director, and three companies suspected of being involved in secret C.I.A. flights. A25

U.N. Report on Syria Hits Snag
Setbacks in the United Nations investigation into the assassination of a former Lebanese prime minister have raised questions about evidence supporting the charge that Syria was responsible for the assassination, according to Western diplomats based in Syria. A3

115 Die in Iran Air Crash
A military plane loaded with Iranian journalists crashed into an apartment building as the pilot tried an emergency landing after developing engine trouble. At least 115 people died, Iranian authorities said. A20

U.N. Fires Elections Director
The United Nations fired Carina Perelli, the director of its highly regarded elections services office on accusations of sexual harassment and abuse of authority. A27

Israel Arrests 15 in Bombing
Israeli security forces, in response to a suicide bombing on Monday that killed five Israelis, arrested 15 suspected Palestinian militants in overnight raids. A5

China Contests Torture Claims
China contested the conclusions of a United Nations envoy and denied that torture was widespread in the country, asking the envoy to revise his views before making a final report on his two-week visit. A5

Britain's New Opposition Leader
Britain's opposition Conservatives chose David Cameron, a 39-year-old product of some of Britain's elite places of learning, as their new leader and likely candidate for prime minister in the next elections. A8

South Africa Arrests Ex-Official
Jacob G. Zuma, the charismatic leader whose dismissal as deputy president last June has unleashed a power struggle in South African politics, was arrested and charged with raping a family friend. A13

NATIONAL A28-31

Terror Suspects Not Guilty, A Jury in Florida Decides
In a major defeat for federal law enforcement officials, a jury in Florida failed to return guilty verdicts on any of 51 criminal counts against a former Florida professor and three co-defendants accused of operating a North American front for Palestinian terrorists. A1

Court Hears Case on Recruiting
In a Supreme Court showdown, the military argued that it should have access to law schools on the same basis as other potential employers, although gay law students need not apply. The law schools promise that only those employers who pledge not to discriminate are welcome. A1

In No Rush to Push DeLay Out
Senior House Republicans said they saw no need to rush party leadership elections to replace Representative Tom DeLay while he contests criminal charges in Texas. A31

U.S. Agrees to Build Plant
The Bush administration, under pressure from other industrialized countries at talks on global warming in Montreal, announced that it had signed an agreement with a coalition of energy companies to build a prototype coal-burning power plant with no emissions. A31

SCIENCE/HEALTH

More Time to Mend Ozone Hole
The layer of ozone in the earth's atmosphere, which protects life from harmful ultraviolet radiation but has been damaged by artificial chemicals, may take a decade or two longer to recover than previously thought, scientists reported. A31

Stem Cell Error Called Minor
An error in an article about an advance in stem cell research arose because the authors supplied the wrong set of replacement photographs and not because of anything that would undermine the article's conclusions, the editors of Science, the journal that published the article, said. A20

NEW YORK/REGION B1-9

Thousands Bid Farewell To Slain Officer in Brooklyn
An estimated 20,000 police officers turned a Brooklyn neighborhood into an ocean of blue in a tribute to Dillon Stewart, a New York police officer who was the first to die in the line of duty this year. B1

4 Dead in Queens Fire
Four people, three of them young children, were killed in Elmhurst, Queens, when a fire tore through the cellar where they lived, Fire Department officials said. B1

New Issue in M.T.A. Talks
The Metropolitan Transportation Authority, which has already angered the transit workers union over its over its demand for cheaper pensions for new employees, made a bold proposal just 10 days before the contract expires: having subway conductors walk through train cars instead of staying in their booths. B3

Pressure Mounts to Rebuild
State, city and Port Authority officials are increasing pressure on Larry A. Silverstein, the developer who controls the World Trade Center site, to relinquish at least a portion of the 16-acre property so that the rebuilding effort can proceed more quickly. B1

Neediest Cases B6

EDUCATION B11

SPORTSWEDNESDAY D1-6

ARTS E1-12

DINING OUT F1-16

OBITUARIES B10

Federik Jacques Philips
The former president of the Dutch electronics giant that bears his family's name, he was 100. B10

BUSINESS DAY C1-18

New Project for Gibson
Mel Gibson, whose ''Passion of the Christ'' was assailed by some critics as anti-Semitic -- and whose father has been on record as a Holocaust denier -- has a new project under way: a nonfiction mini- series for television about the Holocaust, to be developed for ABC. C1

The Battle for Guidant
Johnson & Johnson, responding to Boston Scientific's unexpected $25 billion bid for Guidant on Monday, asserted that the $21.5 billion merger agreement it had reached with Guidant on Nov. 15 represented ''full and fair value.'' C1

Gap's Woes Are Growing
Gap is struggling. Sales are slumping, a string of executives have left in recent months and Wall Street analysts are openly questioning whether the company's leadership is up to the job. C1

Big Board Deal Approved
Members of the New York Stock Exchange voted to approve a merger with Archipelago Holdings, an all-electronic exchange. C3

Business Digest C2

EDITORIAL A32-33

Editorials: Secretary Rice's rendition; Senator Clinton, in pander mode; pushing the envelope.

Column: Maureen Dowd.
